mcbroom1946 wrote:

&gt;There has been much tossed around lately about the frequency of QS
&gt;letters (and how this affects new keyboard layouts.) Here is my humble
&gt;contribution to the question,
&gt;
&gt;For a convenient source, I used two of the largest texts in the files
&gt;section of the Shavian Group: a Sherlock Holmes story (70KB) and a chapter 
&gt;of &quot;The Uses of English&quot; (58KB) The total character count was about 67,000,
&gt;20% of which were spaces.  Of course, all transcriptions are affected by
&gt;the ear of the translator (and I think in both cases it was possibly
&gt;our reknown member Hugh) but we have to start somewhere, and I think the 
&gt;results would much the same with different sources, at least for the first dozen
&gt;letters.
&gt;
&gt;Here are the adjustments made to the originals:
&gt;1) Shavian &quot;array&quot; and &quot;urge&quot; were combined into QS &quot;earth&quot;
&gt;2) Shavian &quot;ado&quot; and &quot;up&quot; were combined into QS &quot;ado&quot; (one form only).
&gt;3) All ligatures were broken down into their components and assigned
&gt;to their root sounds.
&gt;4) Because of the source, of course, no ligatures or letter variants
&gt;were counted. (I think this to be an asset, We should be counting SOUNDS
&gt;not SHAPES!)
&gt;
&gt;Because Yahoo, in their infinite wisdom, will not let me attach the
&gt;chart, I have posted it to the Read files section/resources. Enjoy! Feedback
&gt;appreciated.
